<br>
I agree about the fact that we need to hold the feet of these MMORPG companies to the fire.  I think they are getting away with things that would NEVER fly for 99.9% of software companies.  If they are going to release the game in phases, I want to know their plan for what will be released in each phase.  If they complain that everyone will wait till Phase 4 before buying, too bad, that's life.  It doesn't legitamize downright deception.....<br>
<br>
Don't confuse buggy with "failure to meet requirements" or "not in requirements"<br>
<br>
As a developer, are you suggesting that I write ALL my own software from scratch?  Never purchase or use 3rd person tools/components/objects?  Software is not done that way.  If something out there meets your needs and can be done better, faster, cheaper, by people with more expertise in the area than yourself, I use it.  It's a good business decision.<br>
<br>
Am I to blame for any problems with IIS security holes that affect my customer's web applications?  I can't do anything about it.  I didn't write IIS.  Fixes won't be made until MS makes them.  I write "work arounds" all the time to get around<br>
problems in the 3rd party products I use.  I may have to scale back or change the way a feature is implemented.  But, overall, my customers are better served by my using an already existing web server.  <br>
<br>
I will read up on the NetImmerse engine and come back and comment on it.  I don't know what the engine actually does in the DAoC environment.  But, if I were to write my own MMORPG, I would SERIOUSLY think about using a "world" engine that does all the graphics rendering written by someone else.  My customers would be better served by me spending time on content, variety and features that really set it above and beyond the competition.<br>
<br>
<br>
PLEASE, PLEASE don't tell me you are holding up Verant as the model of an MMORPG game company.  I know Verant is under control of the Anti-Christ.  I am not sure about Mythic at this point... <p>-----------<BR>
